Given a 0-indexed integer array nums, return true if it can be made strictly increasing after removing exactly one element, or false otherwise. If the array is already strictly increasing, return true.
The array nums is strictly increasing if nums[i - 1] < nums[i] for each index (1 <= i < nums.length).

Example 1:
Input: nums = [1,2,10,5,7]
Output: true
Explanation: By removing 10 at index 2 from nums, it becomes [1,2,5,7].
[1,2,5,7] is strictly increasing, so return true.

Example 2:
Input: nums = [2,3,1,2]
Output: false
Explanation:
[3,1,2] is the result of removing the element at index 0.
[2,1,2] is the result of removing the element at index 1.
[2,3,2] is the result of removing the element at index 2.
[2,3,1] is the result of removing the element at index 3.
No resulting array is strictly increasing, so return false.

Example 3:
Input: nums = [1,1,1]
Output: false
Explanation: The result of removing any element is [1,1].
[1,1] is not strictly increasing, so return false.

Approach 1: One-pass greedy check
Time complexity: O(n)
Space complexity: O(1)

public boolean canBeIncreasing(int[] nums) {
    int n = nums.length, peakCnt = 0, peak = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
        if (nums[i] >= nums[i + 1]) {
            peakCnt++;
            peak = i;
        }
    }
    if (peakCnt > 1) {
        return false;
    } else if (peakCnt == 1) {
        if (peak == 0 || peak == n - 2) {            // violation at the start or end,  
            return true;                             // trivially fixable by removing one element.
        } 
        if (nums[peak + 1] > nums[peak - 1] || nums[peak + 2] > nums[peak]) {      // removing nume[peak] if the next number > the previouse one.
            return true;                                                           // removing nume[peak + 1] if the number after next > current.
        } 
        return false;
    }
    return true;                                    // no violation -> already strictly increasing.
}
